## ✅ Pre-push checklist — run BEFORE every push

### 1. TypeScript — use `tsc -b`, not just `tsc --noEmit`

```powershell
cd apps/server; npx tsc --noEmit
cd ../web; npx tsc -b   # <-- project references, same as the real build
```

`tsc --noEmit` passes locally even when `tsc -b` fails on the server.
`tsc -b` respects `tsconfig.json` project references and catches errors
that only appear in the actual build (e.g. conflicting lib settings).

### 2. New npm packages → verify deploy.sh runs `pnpm install`

When adding any new package (`pnpm add ...`), check that `scripts/deploy.sh`
has `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile` BEFORE the build steps. If it's missing, add it.

The server does NOT have local `node_modules` — it only installs what
`deploy.sh` explicitly tells it to. Installing locally and pushing the
lockfile is not enough without this step.

### 3. Service workers (`sw.ts` or any `*.sw.ts`) → exclude from tsconfig.app.json

Service worker files use `lib: WebWorker` types which conflict with
`lib: DOM` in the main app tsconfig. Always add any SW file to
`"exclude"` in `tsconfig.app.json`:

```json
"exclude": ["src/sw.ts"]
```

Vite PWA (injectManifest strategy) compiles service workers independently —
they do NOT go through the main `tsc -b` pipeline.

### 4. TypeScript 5 strict generics (`Uint8Array`, `ArrayBuffer`)

TypeScript 5.6+ makes `Uint8Array` generic: `Uint8Array<ArrayBufferLike>`.
Many Web APIs (PushSubscription, crypto, etc.) expect `ArrayBuffer` specifically.
When converting byte arrays, always return `.buffer as ArrayBuffer`:

```typescript
// ✅ correct
return output.buffer as ArrayBuffer;

// ❌ wrong — fails on server with stricter TS
return Uint8Array.from([...rawData].map(c => c.charCodeAt(0)));
```

